TY  - JOUR
T1  - Good Reasons Sell: Reason-Based Choice Among Group and Individual Investors in the Stock Market
AU  - Barber, Brad M.
AU  - Heath, Chip
AU  - Odean, Terrance
Y1  - 2003/12/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.49.12.1636.25109
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.49.12.1636.25109
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1636
EP  - 1652
VL  - 49
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we compare the investment decisions of groups (stock clubs) and individuals. Both individuals and clubs are more likely to purchase stocks that are associated with good reasons (e.g., a company that is featured on a list of most-admired companies). However, stock clubs favor such stocks more than individuals, despite the fact that such reasons do not improve performance. We describe why social dynamics may make good reasons more important for groups than individuals.
AB  - In this paper, we compare the investment decisions of groups (stock clubs) and individuals. Both individuals and clubs are more likely to purchase stocks that are associated with good reasons (e.g., a company that is featured on a list of most-admired companies). However, stock clubs favor such stocks more than individuals, despite the fact that such reasons do not improve performance. We describe why social dynamics may make good reasons more important for groups than individuals.
